1 Research questions

Main question: There is an effect of sentiment on task performance. (But we dont know what effects what)

POSITIVE
H10: There is no effect of positive sentiment on task performance.
H1A: The more positive sentiment used, the higher the task performance.

H20: There is no effect of reading the self-repair on positive sentiment, all the participants are the same positive.
H2A: Reading the self-repair makes the participants less positive.

NEGATIVE
H30: There is no effect of negative sentiment on task performance.
H3A: The more negative sentiment used, the lower the task performance.

H40: There is no effect of reading self-repair on negative sentiment, all the participants are the same negative.
H4A: Reading the self-repair makes the participants more negative.

INVOLVED
H50: There is no effect of involvement on task performance.
H5A: The more involved, the higher the task performance.

H60: There is no effect of reading self-repair on involvement, all the participants are the same involved.
H6A: Reading the self-repair makes the participants more involved.

ANGER
H70: There is no effect of anger on task performance.
H7A: The more angry, the lower the task performance.

H80: There is no effect of reading self-repair on anger, all the participants are the same angry.
H8A: Reading the self-repair makes the participants more angry.

Game
H90: Game0 success doesnt affect game X success.
H9A: Game0 success makes it more likely that game X will be a success.

*Task performance measured in games completed.

2 Models

POSEMO
glmer(cbind(positive, notPositive) ~ condition + (1 + | dyad)).
glmer(cbind(complete, timeout) ~ posemo + (1 | dyad)) <- only for baseline.
lmer(totalscoreParticipant ~ condition + (1 | Dyad)) <- scores for positive sentiment.

NEGEMO
glmer(cbind(negative, notNegative) ~ condition + (1 + | dyad)).
glmer(cbind(complete, timeout) ~ negemo + (1 | dyad)) <- only for baseline.
lmer(totalscoreParticipant ~ condition + (1 | Dyad) <- scores for negative sentiment

##             (Intr)
## conditinrpr -0.759
## convergence code: 0
## unable to evaluate scaled gradient
##  Hessian is numerically singular: parameters are not uniquely determined

It looks like you have one observation for every value of code. That means that you cant estimate both a residual variance (which is built in to lmer, and linear mixed models more generally) and an among-code variance both of these parameters will be trying to estimate the same variance component, and any combination of var(residual) and var(code) that adds up to the same value will represent an equally good fit to the data.

You also have one observation for every value of meanflow; this is because meanflow is a continuous variable, which is not usually something you want to use as a grouping variable in the model. Im not sure what youre trying to capture with this term.

You can actually fit these models if you insist by using lmerControl to bypass the checks, but you wont necessarily get a sensible result!

Ran model anyway but doesnt necessarily get a sensible result

8.5 Conclusion

H10: There is no effect of positive sentiment on task performance.
H1A: The more positive sentiment used, the higher the task performance.

H20: There is no effect of reading the self-repair on positive sentiment, all the participants are the same positive.
H2A: Reading the self-repair makes the participants less positive.

Since the p-values are lower than 0.05, we keep our 0 hypotheses. No effect of positive sentiment on task performance. No effect of self-repair on positive sentiment.

9.5 Conclusion

H30: There is no effect of negative sentiment on task performance.
H3A: The more negative sentiment used, the lower the task performance.

H40: There is no effect of reading self-repair on negative sentiment, all the participants are the same negative.
H4A: Reading the self-repair makes the participants more negative.

The p-value for the game completion is < 0.05, so there is an effect of reading-self repair on negative sentiment.

Since the p-value for the glmer > 0.05, we keep our H40. There is no effect of negative sentiment on task performance
